Babelsberg/JS Demo World
Un-minimize any window. The ConverterExample and RegionExample are implementations of code examples from the ECOOP'14 paper Babelsberg/JS - A Browser-based Implementation of an Object Constraint Language. What they demonstrate is explained in their help texts. Click also on the links in the text to open ObjectEditors on relevant code. The other windows are further examples. Each window has a help button to explain what the example is about.

    this.child2 = this.get("Rectangle2");

this.addScript(function ChainOfSameExtentsExample() {
    this.layoutSolver = new LayoutSolver();
    
    this.child4 = this.get("Rectangle4");
    this.child5 = this.get("Rectangle5");
    this.child6 = this.get("Rectangle6");
    this.child7 = this.get("Rectangle7");
    // clean up
    bbb.unconstrain(this, "child4");
    bbb.unconstrain(this, "child5");
    bbb.unconstrain(this, "child6");
    bbb.unconstrain(this, "child7");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child4, "shape");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child5, "shape");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child6, "shape");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child7, "shape");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child4.shape, "_Extent");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child5.shape, "_Extent");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child6.shape, "_Extent");
    bbb.unconstrain(this.child7.shape, "_Extent");
    always: { solver: this.layoutSolver
        this.child4.sameExtent(this.child5)
    }
    always: { solver: this.layoutSolver
        this.child5.sameExtent(this.child6)
    }
    always: { solver: this.layoutSolver
        this.child6.sameExtent(this.child7)
    }
    console.log(this);
}).tag([]);
